docs.topic: Tobacco Smoking Cessation in Adults, Including Pregnant Persons: Interventions: pregnant persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians ask all pregnant persons about tobacco use, advise them to stop using tobacco, and provide behavioral interventions for cessation to pregnant persons who use tobacco.
docs.recommendation: You are eligible for a tobacco smoking cessation intervention.

docs.topic: Sexually Transmitted Infections: Behavioral Counseling: sexually active adolescents and adults at increased risk
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends behavioral counseling for all sexually active adolescents and for adults who are at increased risk for sexually transmitted infections (STIs). See the Practice Considerations section for more information on populations at increased risk for acquiring STIs.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a screening for STDs (sexually transmitted diseases).

docs.topic: Rh(D) Incompatibility: Screening: pregnant women, during the first pregnancy-related care visit
docs.description: The USPSTF strongly recommends Rh(D) blood typing and antibody testing for all pregnant women during their first visit for pregnancy-related care.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for Rh(D) blood typing and antibody testing applies specifically to pregnant women during their first visit for pregnancy-related care. As a 28.9-year-old male, you are not eligible for this recommendation.

docs.topic: Anxiety Disorders in Adults: Screening: adults 64 years or younger, including pregnant and postpartum persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for anxiety disorders in adults, including pregnant and postpartum persons.
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get screened for anxiety disorders.

docs.topic: Unhealthy Alcohol Use in Adolescents and Adults: Screening and Behavioral Counseling Interventions: adults 18 years or older, including pregnant women
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for unhealthy alcohol use in primary care settings in adults 18 years or older, including pregnant women, and providing persons engaged in risky or hazardous drinking with brief behavioral counseling interventions to reduce unhealthy alcohol use.
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get screening for unhealthy alcohol use in primary care settings and consider brief behavioral counseling interventions if engaged in risky or hazardous drinking.

docs.topic: Healthy Weight and Weight Gain In Pregnancy: Behavioral Counseling Interventions: pregnant persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians offer pregnant persons effective behavioral counseling interventions aimed at promoting healthy weight gain and preventing excess gestational weight gain in pregnancy.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for Healthy Weight and Weight Gain In Pregnancy: Behavioral Counseling Interventions is intended for pregnant persons. Since you are male, this recommendation does not apply to you.

docs.topic: Healthy Diet and Physical Activity for Cardiovascular Disease Prevention in Adults With Cardiovascular Risk Factors: Behavioral Counseling Interventions: adults with cardiovascular disease risk factors
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends offering or referring adults with cardiovascular disease risk factors to behavioral counseling interventions to promote a healthy diet and physical activity.
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get behavioral counseling interventions to promote a healthy diet and physical activity.

docs.topic: Prediabetes and Type 2 Diabetes: Screening: asymptomatic adults aged 35 to 70 years who have overweight or obesity
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for prediabetes and type 2 diabetes in adults aged 35 to 70 years who have overweight or obesity. Clinicians should offer or refer patients with prediabetes to effective preventive interventions.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a screening for diabetes mellitus.

docs.topic: Ocular Prophylaxis for Gonococcal Ophthalmia Neonatorum: Preventive Medication: newborns
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends prophylactic ocular topical medication for all newborns to prevent gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for ocular prophylaxis with erythromycin ophthalmic ointment applies only to newborns to prevent gonococcal ophthalmia neonatorum. As a 28.9 year old male, you are not eligible for this preventive medication.

docs.topic: Latent Tuberculosis Infection in Adults: Screening: asymptomatic adults at increased risk of latent tuberculosis infection
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for LTBI in populations at increased risk.See the "Assessment of Risk" section for additional information on adults at increased risk.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a screening for Latent Tuberculosis Infection (LTBI) with a QUANTIFERON TB GOLD+ test, which is one of the recommended screenings. Your result was negative, indicating no response to Mycobacterium tuberculosis antigens detected and infection with M tuberculosis is unlikely. No further action is required at this moment regarding LTBI screening.

docs.topic: Hepatitis C Virus Infection in Adolescents and Adults: Screening: adults aged 18 to 79 years
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection in adults aged 18 to 79 years.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) antibody screening.

docs.topic: Aspirin Use to Prevent Preeclampsia and Related Morbidity and Mortality: Preventive Medication: pregnant persons at high risk for preeclampsia
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends the use of low-dose aspirin (81 mg/day) as preventive medication after 12 weeks of gestation in persons who are at high risk for preeclampsia. See the Practice Considerations section for information on high risk and aspirin dose.
docs.recommendation: You are not eligible for the Aspirin Use to Prevent Preeclampsia and Related Morbidity and Mortality recommendation.

docs.topic: Tobacco Smoking Cessation in Adults, Including Pregnant Persons: Interventions: nonpregnant adults
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians ask all adults about tobacco use, advise them to stop using tobacco, and provide behavioral interventions and US Food and Drug Administration (FDA)--approved pharmacotherapy for cessation to nonpregnant adults who use tobacco.
docs.recommendation: You are eligible for a tobacco smoking cessation intervention

docs.topic: Perinatal Depression: Preventive Interventions: pregnant and postpartum persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians provide or refer pregnant and postpartum persons who are at increased risk of perinatal depression to counseling interventions.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians provide or refer pregnant and postpartum persons who are at increased risk of perinatal depression to counseling interventions. However, as a 28.9-year-old male, you are not eligible for this specific recommendation.

docs.topic: Intimate Partner Violence, Elder Abuse, and Abuse of Vulnerable Adults: Screening: women of reproductive age
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians screen for intimate partner violence (IPV) in women of reproductive age and provide or refer women who screen positive to ongoing support services.See the Clinical Considerations section for more information on effective ongoing support services for IPV and for information on IPV in men.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for screening for intimate partner violence (IPV) is specific to women of reproductive age. Given your demographic as a 28.9-year-old male, you do not meet the eligibility criteria for this recommendation.

docs.topic: Osteoporosis to Prevent Fractures: Screening: postmenopausal women younger than 65 years at increased risk of osteoporosis
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for osteoporosis with bone measurement testing to prevent osteoporotic fractures in postmenopausal women younger than 65 years who are at increased risk of osteoporosis, as determined by a formal clinical risk assessment tool.See the Clinical Considerations section for information on risk assessment.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for screening for osteoporosis with bone measurement testing applies to postmenopausal women younger than 65 years who are at increased risk of osteoporosis. As a 28.9-year-old male, you do not meet the criteria for this recommendation.

docs.topic: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infection: Screening: pregnant persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians screen for HIV infection in all pregnant persons, including those who present in labor or at delivery whose HIV status is unknown.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a HIV screening.

docs.topic: Weight Loss to Prevent Obesity-Related Morbidity and Mortality in Adults: Behavioral Interventions: adults
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians offer or refer adults with a body mass index (BMI) of 30 or higher (calculated as weight in kilograms divided by height in meters squared) to intensive, multicomponent behavioral interventions.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation does not apply to you as it requires a BMI of 30 or higher.

docs.topic: Breastfeeding: Primary Care Interventions: pregnant women, new mothers, and their children
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends providing interventions during pregnancy and after birth to support breastfeeding.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for interventions to support breastfeeding is aimed at pregnant women, new mothers, and their children. As a 28.9 year old male, you are not eligible for this specific recommendation.

docs.topic: Prevention of Dental Caries in Children Younger Than 5 Years: Screening and Interventions: children younger than 5 years
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that primary care clinicians apply fluoride varnish to the primary teeth of all infants and children starting at the age of primary tooth eruption.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a ...

docs.topic: Hypertensive Disorders of Pregnancy: Screening: asymptomatic pregnant persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for hypertensive disorders in pregnant persons with blood pressure measurements throughout pregnancy.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommends screening for hypertensive disorders in pregnant persons with blood pressure measurements throughout pregnancy. However, as a 28.9-year-old male, you are not eligible for this screening.

docs.topic: Hypertension in Adults: Screening: adults 18 years or older without known hypertension
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for hypertension in adults 18 years or older with office blood pressure measurement (OBPM). The USPSTF recommends obtaining blood pressure measurements outside of the clinical setting for diagnostic confirmation before starting treatment.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a blood pressure check

docs.topic: Hepatitis B Virus Infection in Adolescents and Adults: Screening: adolescents and adults at increased risk for infection
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection in adolescents and adults at increased risk for infection.See the Practice Considerations section for a description of adolescents and adults at increased risk for infection.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a screening for Hepatitis B Virus Infection showing immunity, as indicated by your Hepatitis B virus surface antibody quantity being consistent with immunity. Therefore, you do not currently require screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection.

docs.topic: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infection: Screening: adolescents and adults aged 15 to 65 years
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians screen for HIV infection in adolescents and adults aged 15 to 65 years. Younger adolescents and older adults who are at increased risk of infection should also be screened.See the Clinical Considerations section for more information about assessment of risk, screening intervals, and rescreening in pregnancy.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a HIV AG/AB 4th GENERATION screening

docs.topic: Hepatitis B Virus Infection in Pregnant Women: Screening: pregnant women
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection in pregnant women at their first prenatal visit
docs.recommendation: You have already received a Hepatitis B virus screening and immunization, indicating you are not currently eligible for the recommended Hepatitis B virus infection screening for pregnant women.

docs.topic: Folic Acid Supplementation to Prevent Neural Tube Defects: Preventive Medication: persons who plan to or could become pregnant
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that all persons planning to or who could become pregnant take a daily supplement containing 0.4 to 0.8 mg (400 to 800 mcg) of folic acid.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for Folic Acid Supplementation to prevent neural tube defects is specifically targeted towards persons planning to or who could become pregnant. Based on your demographic information as a male, you are not eligible for this recommendation.

docs.topic: BRCA-Related Cancer: Risk Assessment, Genetic Counseling, and Genetic Testing: women with a personal or family history of breast, ovarian, tubal, or peritoneal cancer or an ancestry associated with brca1/2 gene mutation
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that primary care clinicians assess women with a personal or family history of breast, ovarian, tubal, or peritoneal cancer or who have an ancestry associated with breast cancer susceptibility 1 and 2 (BRCA1/2) gene mutations with an appropriate brief familial risk assessment tool. Women with a positive result on the risk assessment tool should receive genetic counseling and, if indicated after counseling, genetic testing.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for BRCA-related cancer risk assessment, genetic counseling, and genetic testing applies specifically to women with a personal or family history of breast, ovarian, tubal, or peritoneal cancer or who have an ancestry associated with BRCA1/2 gene mutations. Given that you are a male, you do not meet the criteria for this specific recommendation.

docs.topic: Obesity in Children and Adolescents: Screening: children and adolescents 6 years and older
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians screen for obesity in children and adolescents 6 years and older and offer or refer them to comprehensive, intensive behavioral interventions to promote improvements in weight status.
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get a BMI measurement, using height and weight, as a screening test for obesity. However, the USPSTF recommendation for obesity screening applies to children and adolescents 6 years and older. Given your age of approximately 29 years, this specific recommendation does not apply to you.

docs.topic: Asymptomatic Bacteriuria in Adults: Screening: pregnant persons
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for asymptomatic bacteriuria using urine culture in pregnant persons.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommends screening for asymptomatic bacteriuria using urine culture in pregnant persons. This recommendation does not apply to you as it is specifically for pregnant individuals.

docs.topic: Syphilis Infection in Nonpregnant Adolescents and Adults: Screening: asymptomatic, nonpregnant adolescents and adults who are at increased risk for syphilis infection
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for syphilis infection in persons who are at increased risk for infection.
docs.recommendation: You have already received a RPR, RFX QN RPR/CONFIRM TP test.

docs.topic: Syphilis Infection in Pregnant Women: Screening: pregnant women
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends early screening for syphilis infection in all pregnant women.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for early screening for syphilis infection applies to pregnant women only. As a 28.9-year-old male, you do not meet the criteria.

docs.topic: Prevention of Acquisition of HIV: Preexposure Prophylaxis: adolescents and adults at increased risk of hiv
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends that clinicians prescribe preexposure prophylaxis using effective antiretroviral therapy to persons who are at increased risk of HIV acquisition to decrease the risk of acquiring HIV.See the Practice Considerations section for more information about identification of persons at increased risk and about effective antiretroviral therapy.
docs.recommendation: You are eligible for a preexposure prophylaxis against HIV, as it is recommended for individuals at increased risk of HIV acquisition. However, your medical records indicate that you have undergone screenings for HIV and the results were non-reactive, suggesting no current HIV infection. To assess eligibility, it's important to consider your sexual behavior, use of condoms, number of partners, and any drug use practices as detailed in the USPSTF recommendation. If any of these factors put you at increased risk, PrEP could be beneficial for you.

docs.topic: Cervical Cancer: Screening: women aged 21 to 65 years
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for cervical cancer every 3 years with cervical cytology alone in women aged 21 to 29 years. For women aged 30 to 65 years, the USPSTF recommends screening every 3 years with cervical cytology alone, every 5 years with high-risk human papillomavirus (hrHPV) testing alone, or every 5 years with hrHPV testing in combination with cytology (cotesting).See the Clinical Considerations section for the relative benefits and harms of alternative screening strategies for women 21 years or older.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for cervical cancer screening is specifically for women aged 21 to 65 years. As a male, this recommendation does not apply to you.

docs.topic: Rh(D) Incompatibility: Screening: unsensitized rh(d)-negative pregnant women
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends repeated Rh(D) antibody testing for all unsensitized Rh(D)-negative women at 24 to 28 weeks' gestation, unless the biological father is known to be Rh(D)-negative.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation on Rh(D) Incompatibility screening only applies to unsensitized Rh(D)-negative pregnant women at 24â€“28 weeks' gestation. As a male, you are not eligible for this screening.

docs.topic: Gestational Diabetes: Screening: asymptomatic pregnant persons at 24 weeks of gestation or after
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for gestational diabetes in asymptomatic pregnant persons at 24 weeks of gestation or after.
docs.recommendation: The USPSTF recommendation for screening for gestational diabetes does not apply to you as it is specifically for pregnant persons at 24 weeks of gestation or after.

docs.topic: Unhealthy Drug Use: Screening: adults age 18 years or older
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening by asking questions about unhealthy drug use in adults age 18 years or older. Screening should be implemented when services for accurate diagnosis, effective treatment, and appropriate care can be offered or referred.(Screening refers to asking questions about unhealthy drug use, not testing biological specimens.)
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get screened by asking questions about unhealthy drug use.

docs.topic: Depression and Suicide Risk in Adults: Screening: adults, including pregnant and postpartum persons, and older adults
docs.description: The USPSTF recommends screening for depression in the adult population, including pregnant and postpartum persons, as well as older adults.
docs.recommendation: It is recommended that you get screened for depression
